Add --if-dirty flag to bin/ci to skip redundant runs

tl;dr

When git reports a clean working tree and a sentinel file exists from the
last green run, `bin/ci --if-dirty` exits 0 immediately. This avoids
back-to-back CI runs with no file changes in between (e.g., after commit
pushes, then the next phase gate re-checks).

- bin/ci: Add --if-dirty flag, touch .flow-states/.ci-passed on success
- .claude/settings.json: Widen permission from Bash(bin/ci) to Bash(bin/ci*)
- lib/init-setup.py: Same permission change in runtime source
- skills/init/SKILL.md: Same permission change in reference docs
- skills/commit/SKILL.md: Step 0 uses bin/ci --if-dirty
- skills/code/SKILL.md: Final sweep uses bin/ci --if-dirty
- skills/review/SKILL.md: Pre-transition gate uses bin/ci --if-dirty
- skills/security/SKILL.md: Per-fix step uses bin/ci --if-dirty
- tests/test_bin_ci.py: 4 new tests for --if-dirty and sentinel behavior
- tests/test_permissions.py: Update regex unit test for bin/ci* pattern
